1 BE I T ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
2 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
3 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 6-186.1 of Title 70, unless
4 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
5 A. The Commission for Educational Quality and Accountability
6 shall establish and maintain a two-year pilot program to be known as
7 TeachForwardOK to provide new, high-quality pathways to enter the
8 teaching profession and increase the number of teachers in this
9 state’s workforce.
10 B. Within thirty (30) days of the effective date of this act,
11 the Commission shall issue a request for proposals to select
12 technical assistance providers to evaluate teacher education
13 programs in institutions of higher education within The Oklahoma
14 State System of Higher Education that are accredited by the
15 Commission pursuant to Section 6-186 of Title 70 of the Oklahoma
16 Statutes.
17 C. To participate in TeachForwardOK, a teacher education
18 program shall submit an application to the Commission in the manner
19 and on a form prescribed by the Commission. The Commission shall
20 establish criteria to approve applicants. Subject to the
21 availability of funds, the Commission shall award grants to approved
22 applicant teacher education programs. The Commission may use any
23 gifts, grants, devises, and donations from any public or private
24 source and monies appropriated by the Legislature for the purpose of
Req. No. 1599 Page 2

1 impl ementing the provisions of this section. Grants shall be used
2 as incentives to participate and to contract with a technical
3 assistance provider selected by the Commission pursuant to
4 subsection B of this section. The provider shall evaluate, at a
5 minimum, the following:
6 1. Teacher candidate recruitment and completion;
7 2. Whether the teacher education program prepares teacher
8 candidates effectively;
9 3. Whether the teacher education program meets workforce needs
10 in this state; and
11 4. Innovative ways to recruit nontraditional teacher candidates
12 unique to the teacher education program.
13 D. 1. Evaluation reports prepared by a technical assistance
14 provider shall be electronically submitted to the approved applicant
15 teacher education program and the Commission.
16 2. Within ninety (90) days of receiving the report, the teacher
17 education program shall electronically submit a report response to
18 the Commission detailing how the teacher education program plans to
19 address the evaluation report’s findings. The report response shall
20 prioritize innovative approaches to provide new, high-quality
21 pathways to enter the teaching profession and increase the number of
22 teachers in this state’s workforce including, but not limited to:
23 a. developing a system for recruiting eligible teacher
24 candidates, such as:
Req. No. 1599 Page 3

1 (1) a pathway for high school students to become
2 paraprofessionals,
3 (2) a pathway for paraprofessionals to become
4 teachers, and
5 (3) a pathway for individuals with bachelor’s degrees
6 to become teachers,
7 b. developing a curriculum that includes intensive on-
8 the-job training for teacher candidates,
9 c. identifying a mastery-based evaluation system to
10 determine when eligible teacher candidates have
11 mastered the skills and competencies necessary for
12 graduation from an apprenticeship program and
13 outlining benchmarks that teacher candidates must meet
14 as they progress through on-the-job training,
15 d. offering a schedule that enables teacher candidates to
16 work full time in a public school district while
17 participating in an apprenticeship program and
18 allowing paraprofessionals to continue in their
19 positions, or
20 e. providing a flexible schedule for paraprofessionals
21 participating in an apprenticeship program to support
22 their success in the program that will facilitate
23 course completion and on-the-job training.
